import offline

# Override Plotly's module loading to use our patch instead. # if you get an error, try "sudo pip install -U pyOpenSSL" on the namenode

paragraphs.title: scala - Prepare GCAM Parquet data reading
paragraphs.text:
val FixedExtractGcam = sqlContext.sql("""
select 
V21Date
, Series
, CASE
    when LangLen = 0 then "eng"
    when LangLen > 0 then SourceLanguage
  END
  as SourceLanguage
, FIPS104Country
, Sum_Normalised_Measure
from
(
    select *,length(SourceLanguage) as LangLen
    from BrexitTimeSeries
    -- where v21Date like "2016-05-30%"

) a
""")

FixedExtractGcam.registerTempTable("Brexit")
FixedExtractGcam.show(10,false)

paragraphs.title: scala - Define Data Coverage Check
paragraphs.text:
val qualityCheckCoverage = sqlContext.sql("""
select
  V21Date
, count(*) as RowCount
from 
    ( select 
        from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(V21Date, "yyyy-MM-dd-HH"), 'YYYY-MM-dd') as V21Date
      from BrexitTimeSeries
      where v21Date like "2016%"
      --limit 1000
    ) a
group by V21Date
order by V21Date
""")

qualityCheckCoverage.registerTempTable("qualityCheckCoverage")
qualityCheckCoverage.show(10,false)

paragraphs.title: Filter and Aggregate our Data for Plotting via Pandas/Plotly
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

timeplot = sqlContext.sql("""
Select
from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(Time, "yyyy-MM-dd"), 'YYYY-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.ssss') as Time
, a.Series
, SourceLanguage
--, Country
, sum(Sum_Normalised_Measure) as Sum_Normalised_Measure
from
(
        select
        from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(V21Date, "yyyy-MM-dd-HH"), 'YYYY-MM-dd') as Time
        , SourceLanguage
                    --  , coalesce(FIPS104Country, "unk") as Country
        , CASE
                    --	when Series = 'c3_1'  then "Negative"
                    --	when Series = 'c3_2'  then "Positive"
	when Series = 'c6_6' then "Uncertainty"
    END as   
        Series
        , Sum_Normalised_Measure
        from Brexit 
        where Series in ('c6_6')
        -- Series = 'c4_19'
        and 
        SourceLanguage in ( 'deu', 'fra', 'ita', 'eng', 'spa', 'pol')
        and V21Date like '2016%'
        
) a
group by a.Time, a.Series, a.SourceLanguage --, Country
order by a.Time, a.Series, a.SourceLanguage
""")

sqlContext.registerDataFrameAsTable(timeplot, "timeplot") # python
#//timeplot.registerTempTable("timeplot") // as a note, here's the scala way to do it.

#print(timeplot.head(5))

paragraphs.title: Scala - Filter and Aggregate our Data for Plotting via Scala / Zepp

Select
from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(Time, "yyyy-MM-dd"), 'YYYY-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.ssss') as Time
, a.Series
, SourceLanguage
--, Country
, sum(Sum_Normalised_Measure) as Sum_Normalised_Measure
from
(
        select
        from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(V21Date, "yyyy-MM-dd-HH"), 'YYYY-MM-dd') as Time
        , SourceLanguage
--        , coalesce(FIPS104Country, "unk") as Country
        , CASE
	when Series = 'c3_1'  then "Negative"
	when Series = 'c3_2'  then "Positive"
	when Series = 'c6_6' then "Uncertainty"
    END as   
        Series
        , Sum_Normalised_Measure
        from Brexit 
        where Series in ('c6_6')
        -- Series = 'c4_19'
        and 
        SourceLanguage in ( 'deu', 'fra', 'ita', 'eng', 'spa')
        and V21Date like '2016%'
        
) a
group by a.Time, a.Series, a.SourceLanguage --, Country

""")

paragraphs.title: Convert the Selection to Pandas Data Frame
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

# again note, that to pull in data to pandas from spark, you need to "collect" it. 
# WARNING - do not pull in more data from all the machines than you have in RAM.

explorer = pd.DataFrame(timeplot.collect(), columns=['Time', 'Series', 'SourceLanguage','Sum_Normalised_Measure'])

paragraphs.title: Manually pivot our TimeSeries into Columns for Plot.ly
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
pexp = pd.pivot_table(explorer, values='Sum_Normalised_Measure', index=['Time'], columns=['SourceLanguage','Series'], aggfunc=np.sum, fill_value=0)
timeplot.show(10)

paragraphs.title: Produce our plots using Pandas / Plot.ly
